    <title>What Google rivals want after DOJ’s antitrust trial win</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="An illustration of Google’s multicolor “G” logo" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/i6KFiqB8h24GXp_7RqKUFpWnw64=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73514752/STK093_Google_01.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Illustration: The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="70GAxG"&gt;Longtime Google rivals like Yelp and DuckDuckGo received a huge victory Monday when a federal judge &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/5/24155520/judge-rules-on-us-doj-v-google-antitrust-search-suit"&gt;ruled that Google is an illegal monopoly&lt;/a&gt;. But their statements on the ruling expressed restraint. That’s because the work of restoring competition has just begun, and the judge has yet to decide what that work will include. With a lot of options on the table, Google’s competitors are pushing for changes they believe will help their businesses, which might be harder than it sounds.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="4Hr9XN"&gt;“While we’re heartened by the decision, a strong remedy is critical,” Yelp CEO Jeremy Stoppelman &lt;a href="https://blog.yelp.com/news/us-v-google-decision/"&gt;wrote in a blog post&lt;/a&gt; after the ruling, referencing the new trial phase that will &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/6/24214641/google-us-monopoly-ruling-what-happens"&gt;kick off in September&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
